  <para style="h">John</para>
  <para style="toc1">The Gospel of John</para>
  <para style="toc2">John</para>
  <para style="toc3">John</para>
  <para style="mt2">THE GOSPEL OF</para>
  <para style="mt1">JOHN</para>
  <!--   ************   -->
  <!--   Introduction   -->
  <!--   ************   -->
  <para style="imt">Introduction</para>
  <para style="ipi">John’s Gospel stands apart from the other three—Matthew, Mark, and Luke, the Synoptic Gospels—in more
    ways than one. It’s content is different, it’s chronology is different. The Greek that John uses is very
    simple and is, for the most part, readily translated word-for-word into English. However, underneath
    the simplistic wording is an enigmatic book which makes vague, abstract generalizations it does not explain.
    John’s epistles are even more simplistic yet enigmatic and vague.</para>
  <para style="ipi">On the one hand, John’s writing needs a good copy editing. Among other things, he uses the wrong verb
    tenses, is too ambiguous, assuming that the reader will have no problem filling in the missing content.
    Had I submitted something comparable to the way that John writes as a high school term paper, my English
    teachers would’ve marked it all up in red.</para>
  <para style="ipi">On the other hand, John has his own peculiar meaning of words and phrases that differ from everything
    else in the NT and which can only be learned by studying his writings, the simple, vague phrases which
    are enigmatic and profound. In fact, from a language perspective, John’s Gospel should be viewed in a
    separate light from the remainder of the NT, so different is his writing. Inside this simple fisherman
    was a deeply spiritual man, one who was Semitic and not Western, one who used words and grammatical constructs
    his own ways and not the way everyone else does.</para>
  <para style="ipi">Of all the books in the NT, John’s Gospel has enjoyed preeminence from the days of the early church.
    This is proven by the fact that the oldest surviving manuscripts NT manuscripts, and the most numerous
    of the oldest, are of John. And if Matthew was written to Jews, Mark to Romans, Luke to Greeks, then
    John was written to Christians.</para>
  <para style="ib"></para>
  <!--   **********   -->
  <!--   Chapter  1   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="1" style="c" sid="JHN 1" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="JHN 1:1" />In the beginning<char style="sup">[A]</char> was the Concept<char style="sup">[B]</char>, and the Concept
        was with God, and the Concept was God, <char style="it">having His very nature</char>. <verse eid="JHN 1:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="JHN 1:2" />This person was in the beginning with God. <verse eid="JHN 1:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="JHN 1:3" />Through him all things came into being, and nothing which has come into being came into being apart from
        him. <verse eid="JHN 1:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="JHN 1:4" />In him was life, and the Life was the light of mankind. <verse eid="JHN 1:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="JHN 1:5" />And <char style="it">in the midst of it all</char> the Light shined<char style="sup">[C]</char> in the
        Darkness, and the Darkness couldn’t take it down, overpower it, or contain it<char style="sup">[a]</char>.<verse eid="JHN 1:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="JHN 1:6" />A man sent from God appeared on the scene, and his name was John. <verse eid="JHN 1:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="JHN 1:7" />This fellow came to give an official account<char style="sup">[b]</char>, so that he would give an account
        concerning the Light, so that all would believe through him. <verse eid="JHN 1:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="JHN 1:8" />That fellow was not the Light—instead, he came in order that he would testify about the Light: <verse eid="JHN 1:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="JHN 1:9" />It<char style="sup">[c]</char> was the True Light, that which shines to all mankind, while coming into
        the world<char style="it">, </char>the established order of humans<char style="it">. </char><verse eid="JHN 1:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="JHN 1:10" />He was in and among the world and the world came into being through him, but the world didn’t know<char
        style="sup">[d]</char> him. <verse eid="JHN 1:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="JHN 1:11" />He went to his own particular group of people, and his own didn’t whole-heartedly welcome and embrace
        him<char style="sup">[e]</char>. <verse eid="JHN 1:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="JHN 1:12" />But to whomever whole-heartedly welcomed and embraced him, <char style="it">it was </char>to them he
        gave the authorization and power to become children of God, to those who believe and have faith in his
        established authority<char style="sup">[f]</char>, <verse eid="JHN 1:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="JHN 1:13" />to those who <char style="it">were begotten </char>neither out of <char style="it">spillings of </char>blood<char
        style="sup">[g]</char> nor out of a best-effort of self nor out of carnal desire<char style="sup">[h]</char>
        nor out of the will of a man, but instead were begotten from God.<verse eid="JHN 1:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="JHN 1:14" />And the Concept became flesh and set up camp<char style="sup">[D]</char> among us. We beheld his glory,
        glory as that of an only-begotten <char style="it">issued</char> from the Father, full of grace and truth.<verse eid="JHN 1:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="JHN 1:15" />John testified about him, having cried out, “This fellow here is the one I referred to when I said, ‘The
        one who comes after me has been the center of my attention<char style="sup">[i]</char>, because he was
        (<char style="it">and is</char>)<char style="it"> </char>superior to me.’”<verse eid="JHN 1:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="JHN 1:16" />When you get to the bottom of it all, all of us have received of his fullness, and grace piled on top
        of grace<char style="sup">[j]</char>. <verse eid="JHN 1:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="JHN 1:17" />When you get to the bottom of it all, the <char style="it">Old Testament </char>Law was given through
        Moses; the grace and the truth <char style="it">which we’re talking about </char>came into being through
        Jesus Christ. <verse eid="JHN 1:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="JHN 1:18" />Nobody has seen God fully; God’s only-begotten, who’s in tight with the Father<char style="sup">[E]</char>—that’s
        the person who brought Him out <char style="it">of obscurity</char>.”<verse eid="JHN 1:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="JHN 1:19" />John’s testimony</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:19">When the Judean Jews<char style="sup">[F]</char> sent priests and clergymen<char style="sup">[k]</char>
        from Jerusalem to him in order to ask, “Who are you?”, <verse eid="JHN 1:19"/>
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="JHN 1:20" />he gave them a straight-up answer saying forthrightly<char style="sup">[l]</char>, “Me?—No, I’m not the
        Messiah<char style="sup">[m]</char>.” <verse eid="JHN 1:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="JHN 1:21" />They asked him, </para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:21">“Just who <char style="it">are you</char>? Are you Elijah?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:21">Jumping right in, he said, “No, I’m not.”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:21">“Are you the Prophet?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:21">He answered, “No.”<verse eid="JHN 1:21"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="JHN 1:22" />So they said to him, “Who are you <char style="it">then</char>?—<char style="it">Tell us s</char>o we
        can give a reply to those who sent us. Who do you claim to be<char style="sup">[n]</char>?”<verse eid="JHN 1:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="JHN 1:23" />He said, “I’m a…</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 1:23"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 1:23">“…Voice shouting out in the countryside<char style="sup">[o]</char></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 1:23">Barricade the road the Lord will take!</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 1:23"></para>
    <para style="m" vid="JHN 1:23">“…<char style="it">as written </char>by the Prophet Isaiah.”<verse eid="JHN 1:23"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="JHN 1:24" />Now the ones who had been sent were sent by the Pharisees. <verse eid="JHN 1:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="JHN 1:25" />They posed a question asking, “So now, why do you perform baptisms if you’re neither the Messiah, Elijah,
        nor the Prophet?” <verse eid="JHN 1:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="JHN 1:26" />John replied by saying, “My role is to baptize in water. <char style="it">But s</char>omeone has taken
        a stand in your midst, someone whom you have no first-hand knowledge of, <verse eid="JHN 1:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="JHN 1:27" />someone who follows in my footsteps, someone whom I’m not <char style="it">even </char>worthy of unfastening
        his sandal strap.” <verse eid="JHN 1:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="JHN 1:28" />These things took place in Bethany alongside the Jordan <char style="it">River</char>, the place where
        John was baptizing.<verse eid="JHN 1:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="JHN 1:29" />The next day he saw Jesus coming towards him and said, “Look here—God’s lamb who takes away the world’s
        sin. <verse eid="JHN 1:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="JHN 1:30" />This is the person whom I referred to when I said, ‘A man’s coming who’ll follow in my footsteps, a man
        who has become the center of my attention because he is superior to me because he was in existence before
        I was.’ <verse eid="JHN 1:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="JHN 1:31" />I had no personal first-hand knowledge of him; on the contrary, <char style="it">he was not known even
        to me </char>in order he would become known to Israel <char style="it">all at once</char>. This is the
        reason my role was to come baptizing in water.” <verse eid="JHN 1:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="JHN 1:32" />And John solemnly declared in a statement for the record that he had beheld the Spirit coming down out
        of the sky like a dove and remaining upon him from then on: <verse eid="JHN 1:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="JHN 1:33" />”I had no personal first-hand knowledge of him; on the contrary, the One who sent me to baptize in water,
        He’s the One who said to me, ‘Upon whom you happen to behold the Spirit coming down and remaining upon,
        that’s the person who baptizes in the Holy Spirit.’ <verse eid="JHN 1:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="JHN 1:34" />And I have beheld <char style="it">this event </char>personally and have solemnly attested that this
        person is the Son of God.”<verse eid="JHN 1:34" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="JHN 1:35" />Again, the next day John was <char style="it">just </char>standing <char style="it">there</char>, he
        and two of his disciples, <verse eid="JHN 1:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="JHN 1:36" />and saw Jesus going here and there, and interjected, “Look here—God’s lamb.” <verse eid="JHN 1:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="JHN 1:37" />His two disciples heard him speaking and followed Jesus, <char style="it">in order to become his disciples</char>.<verse eid="JHN 1:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="JHN 1:38" />Jesus turned and saw them following him and, prompting them, said, “What can I do for you<char style="sup">[p]</char>?”
        So they said to him, “Rabbi (which is translated ‘Teacher’), where are you staying?” <verse eid="JHN 1:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="JHN 1:39" />Keeping their curiosity, he said, “Come and see.” So they went and saw where he was staying and remained
        in his company<char style="sup">[q]</char> that day; it was late afternoon around four. <verse eid="JHN 1:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="JHN 1:40" />One of the two who used to be John’s disciples who heard and became his, <char style="it">Jesus’s</char>,
        disciple was Simon Peter’s brother Andrew. <verse eid="JHN 1:40" />
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="JHN 1:41" />First thing he did was to find his brother Simon and tell him, “I’ve found the Messiah” (which translated
        means ‘Christ’). <verse eid="JHN 1:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="JHN 1:42" />He led him to Jesus. Jesus saw him and said, “<char style="wj">You are Simon son of John. You’ll be called
        ‘Cephas’” </char>(which translated means ‘Peter’).<verse eid="JHN 1:42" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="JHN 1:43" />He wanted to depart for Galilee the next day, and he <char style="it">winds up </char>finding Phillip.
        Jumping right in, Jesus said to him, “Be my follower.” <verse eid="JHN 1:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="JHN 1:44" />Now Philip was from Bethsaida, the same city that Andrew and Peter were from. <verse eid="JHN 1:44" />
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="JHN 1:45" />Philip tracked down Nathanael and, figuring he’d get a reply, said to him,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:45">“We found the person spoken of in the writings of the Old Testament<char style="sup">[r]</char>, Jesus
        of Nazareth son of Joseph.”<verse eid="JHN 1:45"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="JHN 1:46" />Nathanael said, “Can anything good come out of Nazareth?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:46">Philip said to him, “Come take a look.”<verse eid="JHN 1:46"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="JHN 1:47" />Jesus saw Nathanael coming towards him and said about him, <char style="wj">“Check it out—a genuine,
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">down-to-earth, </char></char><char style="wj">native son of
        Israel in whom there’s no duplicity or deceit</char><char style="sup">[s]</char><char style="wj">.” </char><verse eid="JHN 1:47" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="48" style="v" sid="JHN 1:48" />Nathanael, starting a conversation, said to him, “Where do you know me from?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 1:48">Jesus replied, <char style="wj">“While you were under the fig tree before Philip hollered for you, I
        saw you.”</char><verse eid="JHN 1:48"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="49" style="v" sid="JHN 1:49" />Nathanael replied, “Teacher, you’re the Son of God, you’re king over Israel.” <verse eid="JHN 1:49" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="50" style="v" sid="JHN 1:50" />Jesus formulated a reply, <char style="wj">“You believe because I said to you that I saw you under the
        fig tree? You’ll see greater things than this.” </char><verse eid="JHN 1:50" />
      <verse number="51" style="v" sid="JHN 1:51" />He continued, <char style="wj">“I’m telling you the honest-to-goodness truth: you’ll see the sky opened
        up and the angels ascending and descending upon the Man</char><char style="sup">[t]</char><char style="wj">.</char>”<verse eid="JHN 1:51" />
    </para>
