  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="5" style="c" sid="JHN 5" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="JHN 5:1" />After these <char style="it">things occurred</char>, there was a Jewish <char style="it">holiday</char>
        festival, and Jesus went down to Jerusalem. <verse eid="JHN 5:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="JHN 5:2" />Among the citizens of Jerusalem, there was a pool at the Sheep Gate (which in Aramaic is called Bethesda),
        which has five porticos. <verse eid="JHN 5:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="JHN 5:3" />In these <char style="it">porticos</char> lay a multitude of those who are feeble with sicknesses of
        one sort or another<char style="sup">[a]</char>, of the blind, the lame, and those with shriveled-up
        <char style="it">limbs</char>, perpetually lying there. <verse eid="JHN 5:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="JHN 5:4" /><char style="sup">[A]</char> <verse eid="JHN 5:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="JHN 5:5" />Now there was a man with a sickness who had been there for thirty-eight years, and his sickness made
        him feeble. <verse eid="JHN 5:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="JHN 5:6" />Seeing this fellow lying there, Jesus, knowing that he had been there for a long time, engaged him in
        conversation and said, <char style="wj">“Do you want to get better?” </char><verse eid="JHN 5:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="JHN 5:7" />The sick man answered, “Sir, I have no person to toss me into the pool when the water’s been agitated<char
        style="sup">[B]</char>. While it’s <char style="it">agitated</char> and I’m on my way <char style="it">to
        the pool, </char>someone else cuts in front of me.<char style="sup">[b]</char>” <verse eid="JHN 5:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="JHN 5:8" />Jesus got to the point and said, <char style="wj">“Get up, pick the cot up, take it, and walk around,”</char><verse eid="JHN 5:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="JHN 5:9" />and the man got better immediately, picked his cot up, and walked around.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 5:9">But that was on a Sabbath. <verse eid="JHN 5:9"/>
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="JHN 5:10" />So now, the Judean Jews proceeded to say to the man who had been healed,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 5:10">“It’s the Sabbath, and you’re not allowed to pick up your cot and take it <char style="it">somewhere</char>.”<verse eid="JHN 5:10"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="JHN 5:11" />He replied, “The guy who made me well told me, <char style="wj">‘Pick it up and walk around’</char>.”<verse eid="JHN 5:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="JHN 5:12" />They asked, “Who’s the person who told you, ‘Pick it up and walk around’?” <verse eid="JHN 5:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="JHN 5:13" />But the man who was healed didn’t know who it was; you see, Jesus had ducked out of sight and into the
        crowd. <verse eid="JHN 5:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="JHN 5:14" />After all of this<char style="sup">[c]</char>, Jesus found him in the temple and said, <char style="wj">“I
        see you’re all better now. Don’t go about sinning, lest something worse happen to you.”</char> <verse eid="JHN 5:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="JHN 5:15" />The man left from there and reported to the Judeans that Jesus was the one who made him better. <verse eid="JHN 5:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="JHN 5:16" />Because of this, the Judeans began to go after Jesus, because he did this<char style="sup">[c]</char>
        on the Sabbath. <verse eid="JHN 5:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="JHN 5:17" />Jesus’s reply to them was, <char style="wj">“Up to the present moment, my Father’s been doing </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">good</char></char><char style="wj"> deeds, and is doing good deeds, and so
        am I</char><char style="sup">[d]</char><char style="wj">.” </char><verse eid="JHN 5:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="JHN 5:18" />So because of this, the Judeans were all the more trying to kill him, because he wasn’t just going about
        freeing <char style="it">people</char> <char style="it">from their sicknesses</char> on the Sabbath,
        but he also kept saying that God is his own Father, making himself out to be equal to God.<verse eid="JHN 5:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="JHN 5:19" />So Jesus proceeded to defend himself, <char style="wj">“I’m telling you the honest-to-goodness truth,
        I really am: the Son can’t do anything that’s from out of himself except for what he happens to see the
        Father doing. For what That One were to do, the Son does these same things and in the same manner. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="JHN 5:20" /><char style="wj">You see, the Father extends his close friendship to the Son and shows him everything
        which He in His own right does, and He’ll show him greater things than these—</char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">good </char></char><char style="wj">deeds, that is—in order to dazzle you all. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="JHN 5:21" /><char style="wj">You see, just as the Father resurrects the dead and breathes life back into them, in
        the same way the Son breathes life back into whom he desires. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="JHN 5:22" /><char style="wj">So—no—the Father doesn’t judge anyone, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">reaching
        a guilty verdict</char></char><char style="wj">, but instead has given the entirety of the judgment </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">of mankind </char></char><char style="wj">to the Son, </char><verse eid="JHN 5:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="JHN 5:23" /><char style="wj">in order that everyone would respect and honor the Son just as they respect and honor
        the Father. He who’s not respecting and honoring the Son doesn’t respect and honor the Father who sent
        him.</char><verse eid="JHN 5:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="JHN 5:24" /><char style="wj">”I’m telling you the honest-to-goodness truth, I really am: he who hears my message
        and believes in the One who sent me has that special fullness of life, eternal life, and isn’t heading
        to a destination of judgment but instead has been transported from the</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">
        </char></char><char style="wj">place of departure of death to the</char><char style="it"><char style="wj">
        </char></char><char style="wj">destination of</char><char style="it"><char style="wj"> </char></char><char
        style="wj">life. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="JHN 5:25" /><char style="wj">I’m telling you the honest-to-goodness truth, I really am: there’s coming a time (and
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">in fact </char></char><char style="wj">the time is now) when
        the dead will hear the voice of God’s Son and they—those who heard it—will live. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="JHN 5:26" /><char style="wj">For just as the Father has life in himself, in the same way the Son too has been granted
        to have life in himself. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="JHN 5:27" /><char style="wj">He has given authority to him to pronounce judgment, because he is the Man</char><char
        style="sup">[e]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="JHN 5:28" /><char style="wj">Don’t be amazed at this, that there’s coming a time in which everyone in the graveyard</char><char
        style="sup">[f]</char><char style="wj"> will hear His voice </char><verse eid="JHN 5:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="JHN 5:29" /><char style="wj">and depart </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">from that place</char></char><char
        style="wj">: those who did the good things </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">that one’s supposed
        to do</char></char><char style="wj"> </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">will depart </char></char><char
        style="wj">to an afterlife</char> <char style="wj">of </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">that special
        fullness of </char></char><char style="wj">life, but those who were in the habit of doing the petty,
        careless, thoughtless, mean, ugly things </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">that one’s not supposed
        to do will depart </char></char><char style="wj">to an afterlife of judgment </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">resulting in a guilty verdict</char></char><char style="wj">.</char><char style="sup">[g]</char><verse eid="JHN 5:29" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="JHN 5:30" /><char style="wj">”I can’t do anything from out of myself; just as I hear I judge, and My Judgment is
        right, since I will not seek the ‘Me-Will’ but rather the will of He who sent me. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="JHN 5:31" /><char style="wj">If I were to formally assert claims</char><char style="sup">[h]</char><char style="wj">
        about myself, my assertions would not be true. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="JHN 5:32" /><char style="wj">There’s Another One who makes formal claims about me, and I know that the assertions
        which He asserts about me are true. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="JHN 5:33" /><char style="wj">You have sent </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">inquiries </char></char><char
        style="wj">to John, and he has gone on record and formally asserted claims by means of the truth. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="JHN 5:34" /><char style="wj">I don’t take to heart and embrace</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char style="wj">
        the formal claims from the human race</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj">, but instead
        I speak these </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">words </char></char><char style="wj">to you that
        you might be spared</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="JHN 5:35" /><char style="wj">That fellow </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">John </char></char><char style="wj">was
        the Set-Ablaze and Shining Light, and you wanted to bask</char><char style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">
        in his light for a moment or two. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="JHN 5:36" /><char style="wj">I, however, have formal claims made concerning me which are greater than </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">those concerning </char></char><char style="wj">John; you see, the works
        the Father has given to me for me to follow through with them—these very works that I do formally register
        claims about me, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">namely</char></char><char style="wj"> that
        the Father sent me. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="JHN 5:37" /><char style="wj">And the One who sent me—the Father—That One formally registered claims about me. You
        have neither heard His voice fully, nor have you beheld His outward appearance. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="JHN 5:38" /><char style="wj">You don’t have His concepts</char><char style="sup">[m]</char><char style="wj"> sticking
        to you</char><char style="sup">[n]</char><char style="wj">, because whom That One sent—you don’t believe
        in that person. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="JHN 5:39" /><char style="wj">Search the Scriptures, since you assume that you have eternal life by means of them.
        Those are where the formal claims about me are registered— </char><verse eid="JHN 5:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="JHN 5:40" /><char style="wj">but </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">even so </char></char><char style="wj">you
        don’t want to come to me in order to acquire that special fullness of life, eternal life.</char><verse eid="JHN 5:40" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="JHN 5:41" /><char style="wj">”I don’t embrace and accept</char><char style="sup">[o]</char><char style="wj"> admiration
        (the praise derived from being one’s pride and joy)</char><char style="sup">[p]</char><char style="wj">
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">heaped upon me</char></char><char style="wj"> from people— </char><verse eid="JHN 5:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="JHN 5:42" /><char style="wj">but no—I have come to know you, that you don’t have the truth of God within you. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:42" />
      <verse number="43" style="v" sid="JHN 5:43" /><char style="wj">I have come being sponsored by my Father and in His authority</char><char style="sup">[q]</char><char
        style="wj">, and you don’t embrace and accept me. If another were to come </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">merely </char></char><char style="wj">by virtue of his own reputation, having no sponsorship
        to speak of</char><char style="sup">[q]</char><char style="wj">, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">then</char></char><char
        style="wj"> you would embrace and accept that guy. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:43" />
      <verse number="44" style="v" sid="JHN 5:44" /><char style="wj">How is it possible for you to believe and have faith, while embracing and accepting
        admiration from others and not seeking the admiration from the One True God?</char></para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 5:44"><char style="wj">“</char><verse eid="JHN 5:44"/>
      <verse number="45" style="v" sid="JHN 5:45" /><char style="wj">Don’t assume that I will submit </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">damning </char></char><char
        style="wj">accusations against </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the lot </char></char><char style="wj">of
        you to the Father. Moses, </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">as defined by what he wrote in the
        Old Testament</char></char><char style="wj">, is the one leveling the </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">damning
        </char></char><char style="wj">accusations—the one in whom you all have set your hope. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:45" />
      <verse number="46" style="v" sid="JHN 5:46" /><char style="wj">You see, if you were occupied with believing and trusting in </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">what</char></char><char style="wj"> Moses</char><char style="it"><char style="wj"> wrote</char></char><char
        style="wj">, you would be occupied with believing in me, as that fellow wrote about me indeed. </char><verse eid="JHN 5:46" />
      <verse number="47" style="v" sid="JHN 5:47" /><char style="wj">If you won’t believe in those verses </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">that he
        wrote</char></char><char style="wj">, how will you believe in my words?”</char><verse eid="JHN 5:47" />
    </para>
