      <char style="fp"></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[A]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[A]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">As he said, “I am,” they thereupon retreated backwards and fell on the ground</char>…The
        glory and holiness of God could not be contained when Jesus spoke the words <char style="it">I am, </char>the
        implication, <char style="it">I am the One-and-Only-One</char>, having just come from an intense time
        of prayer with the Father. These two words, the revelation of the holiness of God, caused the mob to
        fall to the ground.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[B]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[B]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">Chief Priest’s staff</char>…Lit: <char style="it">Chief Priest</char>. The Chief Priest
        is a synecdoche for the Chief Priest’s staff of servants and attendants.</char>
    </note>
  <chapter eid="JHN 18" />
  <!--   **********   -->
  <!--   Chapter 19   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="19" style="c" sid="JHN 19" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="JHN 19:1" />Then Pilate took Jesus and had him whipped, <verse eid="JHN 19:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="JHN 19:2" />plus the soldiers weaved a crown out of thorns and placed it on his head and clothed him in clothing
        one finds on a nobleman<char style="sup">[a]</char>. <verse eid="JHN 19:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="JHN 19:3" />They proceeded to go up to him and say again and again, “Pleased <char style="it">to meet you</char><char
        style="sup">[b]</char><char style="it">,</char> King of the Jews,” and slap him. <verse eid="JHN 19:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="JHN 19:4" />Once more Pilate left <char style="it">the complex </char>and <char style="it">then </char>says to them,
        “Hey, I’m taking him outside, <char style="it">removing him from the complex, </char>so that you understand
        that I haven’t found anything to charge him with.” <verse eid="JHN 19:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="JHN 19:5" />Jesus came out wearing the crown of thorns and the nobleman’s clothing. He <char style="it">then </char>tells
        them, “Here he is<char style="sup">[c]</char>—the man <char style="it">of the hour</char>.” <verse eid="JHN 19:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="JHN 19:6" />When the chief priests and <char style="it">their </char>attendants saw him, they yelled out,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:6">“Crucify! Crucify!”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:6">Pilate <char style="it">then </char>says, “Take him and crucify him yourselves; the fact is, I haven’t
        found anything to charge him with.”<verse eid="JHN 19:6"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="JHN 19:7" />The Judeans answered, “We have a code of law, and according to this code he has to die, since he made
        himself <char style="it">out to be </char>a son of God.”<verse eid="JHN 19:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="JHN 19:8" />So when Pilate heard this remark, he feared all the more, <verse eid="JHN 19:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="JHN 19:9" />reentered the complex, and <char style="it">then </char>says to Jesus, “Are you out of your mind<char
        style="sup">[d]</char>?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:9">Jesus didn’t reply.<verse eid="JHN 19:9"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="JHN 19:10" />Pilate <char style="it">then </char>says, “You won’t talk to me? Don’t you know that I have the authority
        to acquit you or the authority to crucify you?”<verse eid="JHN 19:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="JHN 19:11" />Jesus replied, <char style="wj">“You don’t have any authority at all over me except that which was given
        to you from above. Because of this, the one who betrayed me and facilitated my arrest, handing me into
        your custody, has a worse sin.”</char> <verse eid="JHN 19:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="JHN 19:12" />As a result of this, Pilate proceeded to try to find a way to release him.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:12">The Judeans yelled out, “If you set this guy free, you’re not Caesar’s friend. Everything ‘the king’
        himself has done is in defiance to Caesar.”<verse eid="JHN 19:12"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="JHN 19:13" />Pilate heard these words, brought Jesus out, and seated himself upon the judgment seat at a place called
        the Stone Pavement (which is Gabbatha in Aramaic). <verse eid="JHN 19:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="JHN 19:14" />Now it was around noon on<char style="it"> </char>the preparation day <char style="it">which occurs on</char>
        <char style="it">the day before</char> the Passover. He <char style="it">then </char>says to the Judeans,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:14">“Here he is<char style="sup">[c]</char>—your king.”<verse eid="JHN 19:14"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="JHN 19:15" />Those people yelled out, “Away! Away! Crucify him!”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:15">Pilate <char style="it">then </char>says, “Shall I crucify your king?”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:15">The chief priests replied, “Apart from Caesar we have no king,”<verse eid="JHN 19:15"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="JHN 19:16" />So he then handed him over to be crucified.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JHN 19:16">They laid hold of Jesus <verse eid="JHN 19:16"/>
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="JHN 19:17" />and, lugging his own cross, departed for something called Skull Place (which in Aramaic is Golgotha),<verse eid="JHN 19:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="JHN 19:18" />where they crucified him, and two others with him, one here and one there, with Jesus in the middle.<verse eid="JHN 19:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="JHN 19:19" />In addition, Pilate wrote a sign and put it on the cross; on it was written, “Jesus the Nazarene, King
        of the Jews.” <verse eid="JHN 19:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="JHN 19:20" />It was written in Aramaic, Latin, and Greek, so that many of the Judeans who were near the city where
        Jesus was crucified could read what was written on it. <verse eid="JHN 19:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="JHN 19:21" />The Judean chief priests proceeded to tell Pilate, “Don’t write ‘The king of the Jews,’ but instead <char
        style="it">write,</char> ‘This guy said, “I’m the king of the Jews.”’” <verse eid="JHN 19:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="JHN 19:22" />Pilate replied, “What I’ve written, I’ve written.”<verse eid="JHN 19:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="JHN 19:23" />When the soldiers crucified Jesus, they took his clothing, divided them into four parts, one part for
        each soldier, and <char style="it">they divided up the</char> undergarment<char style="sup">[e]</char>.
        Now the undergarment was seamless, woven in one piece from the top down, <verse eid="JHN 19:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="JHN 19:24" />so they said to one another, “Let’s not rip it <char style="it">into pieces, </char>but we’ll play a
        game of chance for it instead and one person will win it,” in order that the verse of Scripture be fulfilled:</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 19:24"></para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 19:24">They divvied up my outer garments among themselves</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 19:24">And they tossed dice<char style="sup">[f]</char> for my inner garment</para>
    <para style="pi" vid="JHN 19:24"></para>
    <para style="m" vid="JHN 19:24">So—yes—the soldiers did this.<verse eid="JHN 19:24"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="JHN 19:25" />Now Jesus’s mother stood there next to Jesus’s cross; so did his mother’s sister, as well as Mary wife
        of Clopas and Mary Magdalene. <verse eid="JHN 19:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="JHN 19:26" />So Jesus, seeing <char style="it">his</char> mother and the disciple whom he loved standing next to her,
        close at hand, <char style="it">available should she need anything</char>, <char style="it">then</char>
        says to <char style="it">his </char>mother, <char style="wj">“Lady, take a look at your </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">new </char></char><char style="wj">son.”</char> <verse eid="JHN 19:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="JHN 19:27" />Then he said to the disciple, <char style="wj">“Take a look at your </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">new
        </char></char><char style="wj">mother.”</char> And from that time onwards, the disciple took her into
        his household as one of his own.<verse eid="JHN 19:27" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="JHN 19:28" />After these things <char style="it">happened, </char>Jesus saw that everything had already arrived at
        the finishing point. In order to fulfill the Scriptures, he <char style="it">then </char>says, <char
        style="wj">“I’m thirsty.”</char> <verse eid="JHN 19:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="JHN 19:29" />A container full of wine was lying there, so a sponge-full of wine was put on a stick and put to <char
        style="it">his</char> mouth. <verse eid="JHN 19:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="JHN 19:30" />When he took the wine, Jesus said, <char style="wj">“It’s finished,”</char> leaned his head <char style="it">to
        one side</char> and passed away<char style="sup">[g]</char>.<verse eid="JHN 19:30" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="JHN 19:31" />Since it was the day of preparation <char style="it">for the Passover</char>, the Judeans asked Pilate
        if they could break their bones into tiny pieces and take them away, so that the bodies wouldn’t remain
        on the crosses on the Sabbath, since that Sabbath was a high day, <char style="it">being the Passover</char>.<verse eid="JHN 19:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="JHN 19:32" />So the soldiers came and fragmented the bones of the first man and the bones of the other man, those
        crucified with him. <verse eid="JHN 19:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="JHN 19:33" />But when they came for Jesus, as they saw that he’d already died, they didn’t fragment his bones; <verse eid="JHN 19:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="JHN 19:34" />instead one of the solders pierced the side of his rib cage with a spear, and blood and water came out
        right away. <verse eid="JHN 19:34" />
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="JHN 19:35" />One person who had seen this went on record to verify <char style="it">that this did actually happen</char><char
        style="sup">[h]</char>, and his testimony is trustworthy, and that fellow knows that he’s telling the
        truth, so that you all too would believe <char style="it">that this happened</char>. <verse eid="JHN 19:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="JHN 19:36" />In fact, these things happened so that the <char style="it">verse of </char>Scripture would be fulfilled,
        “Not a <char style="it">single one</char> of his bones will be broken,” <verse eid="JHN 19:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="JHN 19:37" />and not only that but another verse which says, “They will look at the one they pierced.”<verse eid="JHN 19:37" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="JHN 19:38" />After these things <char style="it">happened</char>, Joseph of Arimathea, a disciple of Jesus who but
        for fear of the Judeans concealed the fact, asked Pilate if he could take Jesus’s body away, and Pilate
        permitted it. <verse eid="JHN 19:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="JHN 19:39" />And Nicodemus—he who came to him at night—came too bringing a mixture of myrrh and aloes, about 75 lbs.
        (33 kg.)<char style="sup">[A]</char>. <verse eid="JHN 19:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="JHN 19:40" />So they took Jesus’s body and wrapped it in fine linen with the aromas, according to the Jewish burial
        custom.<verse eid="JHN 19:40" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="41" style="v" sid="JHN 19:41" />Now there was a garden in the place where he was crucified, and in the garden was a new tomb in which
        no one had ever been laid. <verse eid="JHN 19:41" />
      <verse number="42" style="v" sid="JHN 19:42" />So on account of the Jewish day of preparation <char style="it">and </char>because the tomb was nearby,
        they then put Jesus <char style="it">in it.</char><verse eid="JHN 19:42" />
    </para>
